AB  - Using a general equilibrium model of North–South trade Graciela Chichilnisky has concluded that if dualism and labour abundance in the South are sufficiently pronounced the export supply curve of that region will be negatively sloped and, as a result, the familiar neoclassical results of an increase in the North's demand for these exports and of an export policy in the South are reversed. We show that the neoclassical results are valid whether or not the supply curve is downward sloping.
