AB  - In a recent issue of this Journal, Chichilnisky (1981) develops a North–South two-good static model to explore the implications of export-led growth policies for the South's terms of trade and income distribution. It is my contention that most of the results of this paper are invalid as stated. Furthermore, I claim that the problems with these results are due in good part to mistakes when dealing with the elementary properties of the model, namely existence, uniqueness, and stability of equilibria. The first part of this note reviews these properties and the main results of Chichilnisky (1981) are discussed in the final part.
