T1  - On the analysis of tariff escalation: Is there a methodological bias against the interest of developing countries?
AU  - Yeats, Alexander J.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
SP  - 77
EP  - 88
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/06/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(84)90005-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387884900051
AB  - For various reasons relating to the achievement of industrialization objectives, many economists have urged that developing countries shift the composition of their exports from primary commodities to semi-finished goods or manufactures. One method for achieving this change is to increase the processing of natural resource based products that are currently exported in their primary (unprocessed) form. However, numerous studies have argued that the tendency of developed country tariffs to increase or ‘escalate’ with the degree of processing is an important constraint to local processing of primary commodities in developing countries. In previous analyses relating to this issue, a tariff bias against processed goods was held to exist when nominal or effective tariffs increased steadily over stages of a processing chain. However, the present study shows that the existence of ‘escalation’ is neither a necessary nor a sufficient condition to establish a bias against processed goods. In addition, once the theoretical basis for establishing such a bias is clearly specified it is apparent that the discriminatory effects of tariffs on processed goods are more important than previously realized. The fact that developing countries have insisted that the issue of tariff escalation be placed on the agenda of the November 1982 GATT Ministerial Meeting highlights the importance of this conclusion.
ER  - 

