AB  - This paper analyses how an industry like mining, where investments take long to complete, adjusts to a permanent decline in demand growth. Optimal control theory is the method used. It is shown that an extended period of excess capacity and low prices will follow after a slowdown in growth. This is because profit maximizing firms will continue to complete projects to which large investment funds have already been committed, even when they anticipate the price fall. Numerical solutions of the control problem, obtained by using parameters relevant to the copper industry, are compared with actual performance of this industry in the late 1970s.
