AU  - Khan, Qaiser M.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
SP  - 313
EP  - 328
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/06/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(84)90021-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438788490021X
AB  - This paper is an attempt to assess the impact on individuals of systematic undernutrition caused by asset and purchasing power constraints. A model is developed linking initial assets to nutrition, nutrition to physical health and physical health to the frequency of sickdays. The cycle is completed by linking the frequency to sickdays to initial assets. The model was tested using a data set from rural Bangladesh and the results support the hypothesis. Those who start below a certain minimum level of assets are caught up in a process of continuous pauperization. Education acts as a brake to this process. The initial thesis that in the absence of outside intervention, asset constraints on nutrition leads to a systematic divestment of human and physical capital is supported in this sample from rural Bangladesh.
ER  - 
